wrecked in the narrowseas,

5
00:00:10.070 --> 00:00:12.530
the Goodwins I think theycall the place,

6
00:00:12.530 --> 00:00:14.500
a very dangerous flat, andfatal,

7
00:00:14.500 --> 00:00:16.130
where the carcasses ofmany a tall ship

8
00:00:16.130 --> 00:00:17.400
lie buried as they say

9
00:00:17.400 --> 00:00:20.470
if my gossip report be anhonest woman of her word.

10
00:00:20.470 --> 00:00:22.330
I would she were as lyinga gossip in that

11
00:00:22.330 --> 00:00:25.330
as ever knapped ginger ormade her neighbors believe

12
00:00:25.330 --> 00:00:28.070
she wept for the death ofa third husband.

13
00:00:28.070 --> 00:00:31.730
But it is true, withoutany slips of prolixity

14
00:00:31.730 --> 00:00:34.270
or crossing the plainhighway of talk,

15
00:00:34.270 --> 00:00:37.930
that the good Antonio, thehonest Antonio--

16
00:00:37.930 --> 00:00:39.230
oh, that I had a title

17
00:00:39.230 --> 00:00:40.870
good enough to keep hisname company.

18
00:00:40.870 --> 00:00:42.170
Come, the full stop.

19
00:00:42.170 --> 00:00:43.600
Hey, what sayest thou?

20
00:00:43.600 --> 00:00:47.500
Why the end is, he hathlost a ship.

21
00:00:47.500 --> 00:00:50.500
I would it might prove anend to his losses.

22
00:00:50.500 --> 00:00:52.600
Let me say amen betimes,

23
00:00:52.600 --> 00:00:56.530
lest the devil cross myprayer,

24
00:00:56.530 --> 00:00:59.270
for here he comes in thelikeness of a Jew.

25
00:01:04.870 --> 00:01:07.400
How now, Shylock?

26
00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:08.930
What news among themerchants?

27
00:01:08.930 --> 00:01:10.230
You knew.

28
00:01:10.230 --> 00:01:12.030
None so well, none so wellas you

29
00:01:12.030 --> 00:01:13.200
of my daughter's flight.

30
00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:14.530
That's certain.

31
00:01:14.530 --> 00:01:16.970
I, for my part, knew thetailor made the wings sheflew withal.

32
00:01:16.970 --> 00:01:19.230
And Shylock, for his own part,knew the bird was fledged

33
00:01:19.230 --> 00:01:20.970
and that it is thecomplexion of them all

34
00:01:20.970 --> 00:01:22.400
to leave the dam.

35
00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:23.730
She is damned for it.

36
00:01:25.630 --> 00:01:27.630
That's certain, if thedevil may be a judge.

37
00:01:27.630 --> 00:01:29.700
My own flesh and blood torebel!

38
00:01:29.700 --> 00:01:31.200
Out upon it, old carrion.

39
00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:33.800
Rebels it at these years?

40
00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:37.970
I say my daughter is myflesh and my blood.

41
00:01:37.970 --> 00:01:41.400
There is more differencebetween thy flesh and hers

42
00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:43.670
than between jet andivory,

43
00:01:43.670 --> 00:01:45.100
more between your bloods

44
00:01:45.100 --> 00:01:48.730
than there is between redwine and Rhenish.

45
00:01:48.730 --> 00:01:51.270
But tell us, do you hearwhether Antonio

46
00:01:51.270 --> 00:01:52.770
have any loss at sea orno?

47
00:01:52.770 --> 00:01:54.130
There I have another badmatch.

48
00:01:54.130 --> 00:01:55.800
A bankrupt, a prodigal

49
00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:58.670
who dare scarce show hishead on the Rialto.

50
00:01:58.670 --> 00:02:02.900
A beggar that was used tocome so smug upon the mart.

51
00:02:02.900 --> 00:02:05.730
Let him look to his bond.

52
00:02:05.730 --> 00:02:07.970
He was wont to call meusurer.

53
00:02:07.970 --> 00:02:09.670
Let him look to his bond.

54
00:02:09.670 --> 00:02:13.230
He was wont to lend outmoney for a Christiancourtesy.

55
00:02:13.230 --> 00:02:15.870
Let him look to his bond.

56
00:02:15.870 --> 00:02:18.300
Why, I am sure if heforfeit thou wilt not takehis flesh.

57
00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:20.030
What's that good for?

58
00:02:20.030 --> 00:02:23.170
To bait fish withal.

59
00:02:23.170 --> 00:02:25.670
If it will feed nothingelse, it will feed myrevenge.

60
00:02:25.670 --> 00:02:28.930
He hath disgraced me andhindered me half amillion,

61
00:02:28.930 --> 00:02:30.930
laughed at my losses,mocked at my gains,

62
00:02:30.930 --> 00:02:33.370
scorned my nation,thwarted my bargains,

63
00:02:33.370 --> 00:02:36.000
cooled my friends, heatedmine enemies,

64
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:37.600
and what's his reason?

65
00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:39.430
I am a Jew.

66
00:02:39.430 --> 00:02:41.470
Ah!

67
00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:45.900
Hath not a Jew eyes?

68
00:02:45.900 --> 00:02:50.900
Hath not a Jew hands,organs, dimensions,

69
00:02:50.900 --> 00:02:53.030
senses, affections,passions,

70
00:02:53.030 --> 00:02:55.700
fed with the same food,hurt with the same weapons,

71
00:02:55.700 --> 00:02:59.430
subject to the samediseases, healed by thesame means,

72
00:02:59.430 --> 00:03:02.000
warmed and cooled by thesame winter and summer

73
00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:03.370
as a Christian is?

74
00:03:03.370 --> 00:03:06.570
If you prick us, do we notbleed?

75
00:03:06.570 --> 00:03:11.830
If you tickle us, do wenot laugh?

76
00:03:11.830 --> 00:03:15.170
If you poison us, do wenot die?

77
00:03:15.170 --> 00:03:20.800
And if you wrong us, shallwe not revenge?

78
00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:26.730
If we are like you in therest, we will resemble youin that.

79
00:03:26.730 --> 00:03:32.270
If a Jew wrong a Christian,what is his humility?

80
00:03:32.270 --> 00:03:34.000
Revenge.

81
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:35.930
If a Christian wrong aJew,

82
00:03:35.930 --> 00:03:40.000
what should his sufferancebe by Christian example?

83
00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:42.170
Why, revenge.

84
00:03:42.170 --> 00:03:46.030
The villainy you teach meI will execute,

85
00:03:46.030 --> 00:03:47.700
and it shall go hard,

86
00:03:47.700 --> 00:03:49.870
but I will better theinstruction.

87
00:03:49.870 --> 00:03:52.730
Gentlemen.

88
00:03:52.730 --> 00:03:55.130
My master Antonio is athis house

89
00:03:55.130 --> 00:03:57.670
and has asked to speakwith you both.

90
00:03:57.670 --> 00:03:59.200
We have been up and downto seek him.

91
00:03:59.200 --> 00:04:04.430
Here comes another of thetribe.

92
00:04:04.430 --> 00:04:08.400
A third cannot be matchedunless the devil himselfturn Jew.

93
00:04:08.400 --> 00:04:10.230
How now, Tubal, what newsfrom Genoa?

94
00:04:10.230 --> 00:04:11.730
Hast thou found mydaughter?

95
00:04:11.730 --> 00:04:14.330
I often came where I didhear of her, but cannotfind her.

96
00:04:14.330 --> 00:04:15.670
Why there, there, there,there!

97
00:04:15.670 --> 00:04:21.170
A diamond gone cost me2,000 ducats in Frankfurt.

98
00:04:21.170 --> 00:04:24.130
The curse never fell uponour nation till now.

99
00:04:24.130 --> 00:04:26.570
I never felt it till now!

100
00:04:26.570 --> 00:04:28.130
2,000 ducats in that

101
00:04:28.130 --> 00:04:31.170
and other precious,precious jewels.

102
00:04:31.170 --> 00:04:34.930
I would my daughter weredead at my foot,

103
00:04:34.930 --> 00:04:37.200
and the jewels in her ear.

104
00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:40.370
Would she were hearsed atmy foot and the ducats inher coffin.

105
00:04:40.370 --> 00:04:41.530
No news of them, huh?

106
00:04:41.530 --> 00:04:42.800
Why so?

107
00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:45.170
And I know not what'sspent on the search.

108
00:04:45.170 --> 00:04:46.530
Why thou--

109
00:04:46.530 --> 00:04:47.670
Shh!

110
00:04:47.670 --> 00:04:49.800
Loss upon loss!

111
00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:54.930
The thief gone with somuch, and so much to findthe thief.

112
00:04:54.930 --> 00:04:59.270
And no satisfaction, norevenge,

113
00:04:59.270 --> 00:05:02.130
nor no ill luck stirring

114
00:05:02.130 --> 00:05:04.070
but what lights o'er myshoulders,

115
00:05:04.070 --> 00:05:07.870
no sighs but o'er mybreathing,

116
00:05:07.870 --> 00:05:10.400
no tears but o'er myshedding.

117
00:05:10.400 --> 00:05:12.670
Yes, other men have illluck too.

118
00:05:12.670 --> 00:05:14.100
Antonio, as I heard inGenoa--

119
00:05:14.100 --> 00:05:15.300
What, what? what?

120
00:05:15.300 --> 00:05:17.000
Ill luck, ill luck?

121
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:19.830
Hath an Argosy cast awaycoming from Tripolis.

122
00:05:19.830 --> 00:05:23.600
I thank God! I thank God!

123
00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:24.900
Is it true? Is it true?

124
00:05:24.900 --> 00:05:27.600
I spoke with some of thesailors that escaped the wreck.

125
00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:30.470
I thank thee, good Tubal.

126
00:05:30.470 --> 00:05:31.900
Good news, good news.

127
00:05:31.900 --> 00:05:33.130
Ha!

128
00:05:33.130 --> 00:05:34.730
Heard in Genoa?

129
00:05:34.730 --> 00:05:36.670
your daughter spent inGenoa, as I heard,

130
00:05:36.670 --> 00:05:38.470
one night, fourscoreducats.

131
00:05:38.470 --> 00:05:43.030
Thou stick'st a dagger inme.

132
00:05:43.030 --> 00:05:46.230
I shall never see my goldagain.

133
00:05:46.230 --> 00:05:49.430
Fourscore ducats at asitting?

134
00:05:49.430 --> 00:05:52.730
Fourscore ducats!

135
00:05:52.730 --> 00:05:55.170
There came divers ofAntonio's creditors

136
00:05:55.170 --> 00:05:56.530
in my company to Venice

137
00:05:56.530 --> 00:05:58.430
that swear he cannotchoose but break.

138
00:05:58.430 --> 00:05:59.800
I am very glad of it.

139
00:05:59.800 --> 00:06:01.230
I'll plague him.

140
00:06:01.230 --> 00:06:02.800
I'll torture him.

141
00:06:02.800 --> 00:06:04.070
I am glad of it.

142
00:06:04.070 --> 00:06:05.330
One of them showed me aring

143
00:06:05.330 --> 00:06:07.770
he had of your daughterfor a monkey.

144
00:06:14.070 --> 00:06:16.200
Out upon her.

145
00:06:18.530 --> 00:06:21.800
Thou torturest me, Tubal.

146
00:06:21.800 --> 00:06:27.330
It was my turquoise.

147
00:06:27.330 --> 00:06:32.200
I had it of Leah when Iwas a bachelor.

148
00:06:32.200 --> 00:06:38.230
I would not have given itfor a wilderness of monkeys.

149
00:06:38.230 --> 00:06:42.800
But Antonio is certainlyundone.

150
00:06:42.800 --> 00:06:44.630
Nay, that's true.

151
00:06:44.630 --> 00:06:48.130
That's very true.

152
00:06:48.130 --> 00:06:51.570
Go, Tubal, fee me anofficer.

153
00:06:51.570 --> 00:06:56.030
Bespeak him a fortnightbefore.

154
00:06:56.030 --> 00:06:59.030
I will have the heart ofhim if he forfeit,

155
00:06:59.030 --> 00:07:01.130
for were he out of Venice,

156
00:07:01.130 --> 00:07:04.200
I can make whatmerchandise I will.

157
00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:08.270
Go, Tubal, and meet me atour synagogue.

158
00:07:12.230 --> 00:07:15.200
Go, good Tubal.

159
00:07:17.700 --> 00:07:21.530
At our synagogue, Tubal.

160
00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:35.930
I pray you, tarry,

161
00:07:35.930 --> 00:07:39.500
pause a day or two beforeyou hazard,

162
00:07:39.500 --> 00:07:42.900
for in choosing wrong, Ilose your company.

163
00:07:42.900 --> 00:07:46.200
Therefore, forbear awhile.

164
00:08:03.570 --> 00:08:07.830
There's something tellsme-- but it is not love--

165
00:08:07.830 --> 00:08:09.900
I would not lose you.

166
00:08:09.900 --> 00:08:14.170
And you know yourself hatecounsels not in such a quality.

167
00:08:14.170 --> 00:08:17.870
But lest you should notunderstand me well--

168
00:08:17.870 --> 00:08:21.500
and yet a maiden hath notongue but thought--

169
00:08:21.500 --> 00:08:24.370
I would detain you heresome month or two

170
00:08:24.370 --> 00:08:25.830
before you venture for me.

171
00:08:29.570 --> 00:08:31.930
I could teach you how tochoose right,

172
00:08:31.930 --> 00:08:34.730
but then I am forsworn.

173
00:08:34.730 --> 00:08:39.000
So will I never be.

174
00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:41.330
So may you miss me.

175
00:08:41.330 --> 00:08:43.000
but if you do, you'll makeme wish a sin

176
00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:46.830
that I had been forsworn.

177
00:08:46.830 --> 00:08:49.470
Beshrew your eyes.

178
00:08:49.470 --> 00:08:54.100
They have o'erlooked meand divided me.

179
00:08:54.100 --> 00:08:59.930
One half of me is yours,the other half, yours.

180
00:08:59.930 --> 00:09:04.200
Mine own, I would say, butif mine, then yours,

181
00:09:04.200 --> 00:09:06.230
and so all yours.

182
00:09:08.130 --> 00:09:10.600
Oh, these naughty timesput bars

183
00:09:10.600 --> 00:09:12.330
between the owners andtheir rights.

184
00:09:12.330 --> 00:09:15.170
And so, though yours,

185
00:09:15.170 --> 00:09:17.330
not yours.

186
00:09:17.330 --> 00:09:18.570
Prove it so,

187
00:09:18.570 --> 00:09:20.670
let fortune go to hell forit, not I.

188
00:09:20.670 --> 00:09:25.870
I speak too long, but 'tisto piece the time,

189
00:09:25.870 --> 00:09:27.870
to eke it and to draw itout in length

190
00:09:27.870 --> 00:09:29.700
to stay you from election.

191
00:09:29.700 --> 00:09:33.370
Let me choose, for as Iam, I live upon the rack.

192
00:09:33.370 --> 00:09:35.300
Upon the rack, Bassanio?

193
00:09:35.300 --> 00:09:36.400
Then confess.

194
00:09:36.400 --> 00:09:38.330
What treason is theremingled with your love?

195
00:09:38.330 --> 00:09:41.370
None but that ugly treasonof mistrust

196
00:09:41.370 --> 00:09:43.870
which makes me fear theenjoying of my love.

197
00:09:43.870 --> 00:09:46.070
There may as well be amityin life

198
00:09:46.070 --> 00:09:48.970
'tween snow and fire astreason and my love.

199
00:09:48.970 --> 00:09:50.600
Ay, but I fear you speakupon the rack

200
00:09:50.600 --> 00:09:52.530
where men enforced dospeak anything.

201
00:09:52.530 --> 00:09:55.400
Promise me life, and I'llconfess the truth.

202
00:09:55.400 --> 00:09:58.500
Well, then, confess andlive.

203
00:09:58.500 --> 00:10:01.930
Confess and love had beenthe very sum of myconfession.

204
00:10:01.930 --> 00:10:03.800
Oh, happy torment

205
00:10:03.800 --> 00:10:07.100
when my torturer dothteach me answers fordeliverance.

206
00:10:07.100 --> 00:10:10.570
But let me to my fortuneand the caskets.

207
00:10:10.570 --> 00:10:13.900
Away then.

208
00:10:13.900 --> 00:10:16.600
I am locked in one ofthem.

209
00:10:16.600 --> 00:10:19.270
If you do love me, youwill find me out.

210
00:10:27.830 --> 00:10:33.300
Nerissa and the rest,stand all aloof.

211
00:10:33.300 --> 00:10:35.800
Let music sound while hedoth make his choice,

212
00:10:35.800 --> 00:10:39.570
then if he lose,

213
00:10:39.570 --> 00:10:43.500
he makes a swan-like endfading in music.

214
00:10:43.500 --> 00:10:46.630
That the comparison maystand more proper,

215
00:10:46.630 --> 00:10:50.200
my eye shall be the streamand watery deathbed forhim.

216
00:10:50.200 --> 00:10:54.800
He may win, and what ismusic then?

217
00:10:54.800 --> 00:10:57.870
Why then music is even asthe flourish

218
00:10:57.870 --> 00:11:01.170
when new subjects bow to anew-crowned monarch.

219
00:11:01.170 --> 00:11:04.300
Such it is as are thosedulcet sounds at break ofday

220
00:11:04.300 --> 00:11:06.770
that creep into thedreaming bridegroom's ear

221
00:11:06.770 --> 00:11:09.800
and summon him tomarriage.

222
00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:13.670
Now he goes, with no lesspresence,

223
00:11:13.670 --> 00:11:17.630
but with much more lovethan young Alcaides

224
00:11:17.630 --> 00:11:19.270
when he did redeem thevirgin tribute

225
00:11:19.270 --> 00:11:23.070
paid by howling Troy tothe sea monster.

226
00:11:23.070 --> 00:11:24.970
I stand for sacrifice.

227
00:11:24.970 --> 00:11:28.830
The rest aloof are theDardanian wives

228
00:11:28.830 --> 00:11:30.670
with bleared visages

229
00:11:30.670 --> 00:11:33.000
come forth to view theissue of the exploit.

230
00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:39.300
Go, Hercules.

231
00:11:39.300 --> 00:11:40.570
Live thou; I live.

232
00:11:40.570 --> 00:11:44.800
With much, much moredismay, I view the fight

233
00:11:44.800 --> 00:11:47.270
than thou that makes thefray.

234
00:11:49.370 --> 00:12:03.430
Tell me where is fancybred?

235
00:12:03.430 --> 00:12:11.200
Or in the heart or in thehead?

236
00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:21.930
How begot, how nourished?

237
00:12:21.930 --> 00:12:29.200
Reply, reply.

238
00:12:29.200 --> 00:12:39.130
It is engendered in theeyes

239
00:12:39.130 --> 00:12:44.370
with gazing fed,

240
00:12:44.370 --> 00:12:50.770
and fancy dies

241
00:12:50.770 --> 00:13:05.230
in the cradle where itlies.

242
00:13:05.230 --> 00:13:17.430
Let us all ring fancy'sknell.

243
00:13:17.430 --> 00:13:23.170
I'll begin it.

244
00:13:23.170 --> 00:13:26.030
Ding, dong, bell.

245
00:13:28.800 --> 00:13:31.530
Ding, dong, bell.

246
00:13:34.130 --> 00:13:36.800
Ding, dong, bell.

247
00:13:39.230 --> 00:13:41.970
Ding, dong, bell.

248
00:13:49.470 --> 00:13:54.930
So may the outward showsbe least themselves.

249
00:13:54.930 --> 00:14:00.900
The world is stilldeceived with ornament.

250
00:14:00.900 --> 00:14:05.430
In law, what plea sotainted and corrupt

251
00:14:05.430 --> 00:14:08.330
but being seasoned with agracious voice

252
00:14:08.330 --> 00:14:10.870
obscures the show of evil?

253
00:14:10.870 --> 00:14:14.630
In religion, what damnederror

254
00:14:14.630 --> 00:14:17.200
but some sober brow willbless it,

255
00:14:17.200 --> 00:14:18.670
and approve it with atext,

256
00:14:18.670 --> 00:14:22.270
hiding the grossness withfair ornament?

257
00:14:22.270 --> 00:14:23.470
There is no vice so simple

258
00:14:23.470 --> 00:14:26.000
but assumes some mark ofvirtue

259
00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:27.930
on his outward parts.

260
00:14:27.930 --> 00:14:30.030
How many cowards,

261
00:14:30.030 --> 00:14:34.400
whose hearts are all asfalse as stairs of sand,

262
00:14:34.400 --> 00:14:36.430
wear yet upon their chins

263
00:14:36.430 --> 00:14:39.200
the beards of Hercules andfrowning Mars,

264
00:14:39.200 --> 00:14:43.300
who inward searched, havelivers white as milk.

265
00:14:43.300 --> 00:14:45.900
And these assume butvalor's excrement

266
00:14:45.900 --> 00:14:48.070
to render them redoubted.

